  "opinion": "As a curious young man navigating the challenges of STEM education in Milan, I've come to understand stereotype threat not just as a theoretical concept but as a tangible barrier that affects my peers and me daily. Stereotype threat occurs when individuals internalize negative stereotypes about their group's abilities, leading to anxiety and reduced performance. In Italian universities, where STEM fields are often perceived as 'for the smart'—a stereotype that disproportionately affects women and underrepresented minorities—I've witnessed how this anxiety can manifest in class. For instance, during group projects, some students hesitate to contribute because they fear their ideas might be dismissed as 'not good enough.' This isn't just about individual performance; it's about the systemic underrepresentation we see in these fields. Addressing it requires more than just awareness—it demands structural changes. Universities should implement mentorship programs that pair students with role models who've succeeded in STEM despite similar stereotypes. Additionally, fostering inclusive classroom environments where all voices are valued can help reduce the fear of failure. I've also found that peer support networks, like study groups focused on collaborative problem-solving, significantly lower anxiety. As someone who values both intellectual rigor and empathy, I believe that by creating spaces where students feel safe to make mistakes and learn from them, we can dismantle these barriers. It's not just about fixing the problem but building a culture where diversity isn't just encouraged but celebrated as a strength.",
